At site A are two small, oblong explosion craters, oriented about S30Â°E (fig. 9).
The larger is 60 m long and 30 m wide, and has a shallow, red turbid lake.
Gouging by fumarolic and boiling-spring activity has exposed strata in the north wall of the crater, which rises 7 m above the lake bed.
The crater rim is mantled with a 1.5-m-thick ring of well-bedded ejecta.
The beds vary from 0.5 cm to several cm thick and consist of poorly sorted silt, sand, and pebble-sized lithic fragments cemented by hydrothermal alteration.
The tephra beds in turn overlie what Lack of surface appears to be glacial drift exposed in the crater wall.
erosion indicates the craters are postglacial features.
The craters probably formed as a result of a series of phreatic explosions that may Explosion have occurred during the waning stages of valley deglaciation. craters in geothermal fields have been correlated with deglaciation elsewhere, e.g. Yellowstone National Pafk (Muffler and others, 1971).
Thermal-vent characteristics The most distinctive feature at site A is the small, red-stained crater lake measuring about 30 m long and 15 m wide.
The principal thermal vents occur at the northwest end of the lake, where several vigorously boiling springs and steam vents are carving a cavern into the side of the hematite-stained crater wall.
The crater wall and rim are pock marked with numerous small vapor vents that are often ringed with yellowcolored sublimates.
Most of the ground surrounding the lake has been hydrothermally altered to red, yellow, and,gray clays.
Several meters south of the lake are some filled with bubbling mud.
Parts of also themally active, again consisting of vents.
The hollow of this smaller crater area.
sever;1 0.5-m-dia steam caverns, the adjacent smaller crater are small mudpots and steam contains a warm, marshy
The northwest flanks of the craters are steep and drop about 15 m to a cold stream-channel.
Temperaturesin the soil at 10 cm depth measured 500 to 9SÂ°C near the crater rim and 22'C near the stream channel.
Several warm seeps and small hot springs measuring up to 750~ were observed issuing from the stream bank below the crater.
The area southeast of the craters is also warm, measuring 64OC at a depth of 10 cm at a distance of 20 m from the larger crater rim.
Thermal activity at site B is much less intense than at A.
The site consists of a series of hot mudpots, turbid pools, bubbling warm springs, several small steam vents and generally warm marshy ground (fig. 9).
This activity occurs in a bowl like feature iith the thermal waters and steam emanating from the alluvial and colluvial cover, which may be underlain by glacial deposits.
The warm waters drain from the bowl to both the east and west.
Table 4 gives the chemical composition and physical properties of thermal waters obtained from the two Korovin sites.
The water sample from site A was obtained from a vigorously boiling pool at the northwest end of the crater lake.
The water sample from site B was taken from a -3a-
small hot spring pool, measuring 48Â°C with a low.discharge.
Both spring Spring samples are distinguished by very low concentration of chlorides. water from B is much more dilute, much lower in sulfate, and nearer neutral pH than water from site A.
The higher concentration of cations at site A--- particularly Ca and Mg--- is probably partially due to hot acid waters attacking and leaching the surrounding rocks, The acidity probably The odor of results from the oxidation of H2S to form sulfuric acid.
H2S was noticeable at site A and a trace amount was detected in the water.
